# SFGL v1.0 — Structural Framework Governance License  
## Constraint-Native Infrastructure Governance (CNIG)

Copyright (c) 2026  
Gaurav H. Thanki  

---

## 1. Purpose

This license governs the use of:

Constraint-Native Infrastructure Governance (CNIG)

CNIG is a conceptual framework for reasoning about admissible system states within reachable state space under composition constraints prior to execution.

It is intended for:

systems interpretation  
architectural reasoning  
research and academic analysis  
design-time discussion of distributed systems behavior  

CNIG is not a system, product, or execution framework.

---

## 2. Nature of CNIG

CNIG is:

a conceptual reasoning model  
a vocabulary for compositional system analysis  
a lens for describing emergent behavior in distributed systems  

CNIG is not:

a runtime system  
a policy enforcement engine  
a compliance framework  
a formal verification system  
a decision-making authority in operational environments  

---

## 3. Permitted Use

CNIG may be used for:

reading and interpretation  
academic research and citation  
systems design discussion  
architectural review and analysis  
non-commercial experimentation  
internal organizational discussion of system behavior  

All use must comply with Sections 5 and 6 (Attribution + Non-Authority Clause).

---

## 4. Commercial Context Use

CNIG may be referenced in commercial environments only as:

a conceptual reasoning framework used in design and analysis  

It may NOT be:

packaged as a product or feature  
sold as a methodology or governance system  
embedded into proprietary systems as an implicit control layer  
used as a branding replacement for internal engineering processes  

---

## 5. Attribution Requirement (Invariant Clause)

All uses, references, derivations, and implementations of CNIG must preserve the following attribution verbatim:

Constraint-Native Infrastructure Governance (CNIG) by Gaurav H. Thanki  

This attribution must appear in:

academic publications  
technical documentation  
system design documents where CNIG is referenced  
derivative conceptual frameworks  
architectural analysis or incident reports referencing CNIG  

Attribution must not be:

removed  
anonymized  
shortened in a way that removes authorship  
replaced with partial references such as “based on CNIG” without author inclusion  

---

## 6. Non-Authority Clause (CRITICAL HARDENING)

CNIG has no operational authority in any system in which it is referenced.

Specifically:

CNIG may not be used to approve or deny system changes  
CNIG may not be encoded into CI/CD gating logic  
CNIG may not be implemented as runtime policy enforcement  
CNIG may not be used as a compliance or certification requirement  
CNIG may not be treated as executable governance logic  

Any system that references CNIG must treat it strictly as:

an interpretive model with no control-plane authority  

---

## 7. Terminology Integrity Clause

The following terms are canonical CNIG identifiers:

Primitives  
Invariants  
Failure Modes  
Reachable State Space  
Admissible System State  
Composition Constraints  
Execution vs Governance Separation  

These terms may be extended or interpreted, but:

they must remain traceably associated with CNIG and must not be rebranded in a way that obscures origin.

---

## 8. Restriction Boundary

CNIG may not be represented as:

a production governance system  
a safety-certified system  
a runtime enforcement mechanism  
a formal verification guarantee system  
a deployable compliance framework  

This applies regardless of modification, embedding, or derivative interpretation.

---

## 9. Epistemic Limitation

CNIG does not claim:

implementation completeness  
correctness guarantees  
universal applicability  
formal verification completeness  

Any implementation of CNIG is an interpretation, not a canonical instantiation.

---

## 10. Liability Limitation

The author is not liable for:

system designs influenced by CNIG  
operational misuse or misinterpretation  
production failures in systems referencing CNIG  
derivative implementations or adaptations  

---

## 11. Canonical Reference

Constraint-Native Infrastructure Governance (CNIG)  
by Gaurav H. Thanki  

---

## 12. Final Clause (Structural Preservation Rule)

CNIG may be referenced, studied, and implemented as a conceptual framework.

However:

CNIG must never function as an authority layer over any operational system.

All implementations must preserve the separation between:

interpretation (CNIG)  
execution (system runtime)
